.TH "Intl.Locale.hourCycle" "JS" "August 21, 2023" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Intl.Locale.hourCycle \- Intl.Locale.prototype.hourCycle
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]hourCycle\f[B]\f[R] accessor property of
\f[CR]Intl.Locale\f[R] instances returns the hour cycle type for this
locale.
.SH DESCRIPTION
There are 2 main types of time keeping conventions (clocks) used around
the world: the 12 hour clock and the 24 hour clock.
The \f[CR]hourCycle\f[R] property\[cq]s value is set at construction
time, either through the \f[CR]hc\f[R] key of the locale identifier or
through the \f[CR]hourCycle\f[R] option of the \f[CR]Intl.Locale()\f[R]
constructor.
The latter takes priority if they are both present; and if neither is
present, the property has value \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
.PP
For a list of supported hour cycle types, see
\f[CR]Intl.Locale.prototype.getHourCycles()\f[R].
.PP
The set accessor of \f[CR]hourCycle\f[R] is \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
You cannot change this property directly.
.SH EXAMPLES
Like other locale subtags, the hour cycle type can be added to the
\f[CR]Intl.Locale\f[R] object via the locale string, or a configuration
object argument to the constructor.
.SS Adding an hour cycle via the locale string
In the \c
.UR https://www.unicode.org/reports/tr35/
Unicode locale string spec
.UE \c
, hour cycle types are locale key \[lq]extension subtags\[rq].
These subtags add additional data about the locale, and are added to
locale identifiers by using the \f[CR]\-u\f[R] extension.
Thus, the hour cycle type can be added to the initial locale identifier
string that is passed into the \f[CR]Intl.Locale()\f[R] constructor.
To add the hour cycle type, first add the \f[CR]\-u\f[R] extension key
to the string.
Next, add the \f[CR]\-hc\f[R] extension to indicate that you are adding
an hour cycle.
Finally, add the hour cycle type to the string.
.IP
.EX
const locale = new Intl.Locale(\[dq]fr\-FR\-u\-hc\-h23\[dq]);
console.log(locale.hourCycle); // \[dq]h23\[dq]
.EE
.SS Adding an hour cycle via the configuration object argument
The \f[CR]Intl.Locale()\f[R] constructor has an optional configuration
object argument, which can contain any of several extension types,
including hour cycle types.
Set the \f[CR]hourCycle\f[R] property of the configuration object to
your desired hour cycle type, and then pass it into the constructor.
.IP
.EX
const locale = new Intl.Locale(\[dq]en\-US\[dq], { hourCycle: \[dq]h12\[dq] });
console.log(locale.hourCycle); // \[dq]h12\[dq]
.EE
